Shared Qs (u04)


  1. Question

    Jason drew two overlapping rectangles on a 10x10 grid.


    Let’s call the red rectangle A and the blue rectangle B. Find the following areas:

    • Area covered by A = squares
    • Area covered by B = squares
    • Area covered by the intersection of A and B = squares
    • Area covered by the union of A and B = squares
    • Area covered by ONLY A (and not B) = squares
    • Area covered by ONLY B (and not A) = squares
    • Area not covered (neither A nor B) = squares


    Solution

    • Area covered by A = 10
    • Area covered by B = 16
    • Area covered by the intersection of A and B = 4
    • Area covered by the union of A and B = 22
    • Area covered by ONLY A (and not B) = 6
    • Area covered by ONLY B (and not A) = 12
    • Area not covered (neither A nor B) = 78

  11. Question

    In a school, there are two clubs: club A and club B. Students can join one club, both clubs, or neither club.

    • The number of students in at least one club is 40.
    • The total number of students in the school is 47.
    • The number of students in only club A (and not club B) is 2.
    • The number of students in club A is 25.

    Calculate the following:

    • How many students are in BOTH clubs? students
    • How many students are in neither club? students
    • How many students are only in club B (and not club A)? students
    • How many students are in club B? students


    Solution

    • The number of students in both clubs (in A and B) is 23.
    • The number of students in neither club is 7.
    • The number of students in only club B (and not club A) is 15.
    • The number of students in club B is 38.

  21. Question

    In symbolic logic, we often use the following symbols for NOT, AND, and OR:

    \[\neg ~=~ \text{not}\] \[\cap ~=~ \text{and} ~=~ \text{intersection}\] \[\cup ~=~ \text{or} ~=~ \text{union}\]

    In this case (and almost always), unary operators (like \(\neg\)) have higher precedence than binary operators (like \(\cup\) and \(\cap\)).

    You are given the following probabilities (regarding events \(A\) and \(B\)).

    • \(P(\neg A\cap B)=0.3\)
    • \(P(A\cup B)=0.61\)
    • \(P(A\cap B)=0.14\)

    Calculate the following:

    • \(P(B)=\) students
    • \(P(A\cap \neg B)=\) students
    • \(P(\neg A\cap \neg B)=\) students
    • \(P(\neg B)\) students
    • \(P(A)=\) students
    • \(P(\neg A)\) students

    Optional metaphorical context

    Imagine getting blindfolded and throwing darts at a board far away on a gusty day. On that board are two overlapping circles: circle A and circle B. If you miss the board completely, the throw does not count, and you try again. If you hit circle A, that counts as event \(A\). If you miss circle A (but hit the board), that counts as \(\neg A\). The probability that you hit circle A will depend on the proportion of the board’s area taken up by circle A.

    \[P(A) ~=~ \frac{\text{area of circle A}}{\text{area of board}}\] \[P(\neg A) ~=~ \frac{\text{area of board} ~~-~~ \text{area of circle A}}{\text{area of board}}\]



    Solution

    • \(P(B)=0.44\)
    • \(P(A\cap \neg B)=0.17\)
    • \(P(\neg A \cap \neg B)=0.39\)
    • \(P(\neg B)=0.56\)
    • \(P(A)=0.31\)
    • \(P(\neg A)=0.69\)

    You might find it helpful to draw a Venn diagram.

    • NOTE: These areas are not drawn to scale.

  31. Question

    • Events \(A\) and \(B\) are mutually exclusive if and only if \(P(A \cap B)=0\).
    • Events \(A\) and \(B\) are independent if and only if \(P(A \cap B)=P(A)\cdot P(B)\).

    Consider the following:

    \[P(A)=0.16\]

    \[P(B)=0.25\]

    \[P(A \cup B)=0.37\]

    Are events \(A\) and \(B\) independent, mutually exclusive, or neither?


    1. Independent
    2. Mutually exclusive
    3. Neither

    Solution

    First, find the probability of getting A and B.

    \[P(A \cap B) ~=~ P(A)+P(B)-P(A \cup B)\]

    \[P(A \cap B) ~=~ 0.16+0.25-0.37\]

    \[P(A \cap B) ~=~ 0.04\]

    Notice \(P(A \cap B)=0.04\). Also \(P(A)\cdot P(B)=0.16\cdot0.25=0.04\) so events A and B are independent.

  41. Question

    In a deck of strange cards, there are 382 cards. Each card has an image and a color. The number of repeats of each image-color combination is shown in the table below.

    white teal red black Total
    house 49 18 42 40 149
    quilt 41 38 23 39 141
    rug 19 10 20 43 92
    Total 109 66 85 122 382
    1. What is the probability a random card is a rug?
    2. What is the probability a random card is teal?
    3. What is the probability a random card is both a house and black?
    4. What is the probability a random card is either a quilt or black (or both)?
    5. What is the probability a random card is white given it is a house?
    6. What is the probability a random card is a quilt given it is black?
    7. Between a house and a rug, which is more likely to be a teal?


    Solution

    video

    The key logical terms are “and”, “or”, and “given”. Notice that I am using “given” as a shorter version of “under the condition”.

    1. \(P(\text{rug})=\frac{92}{382}=0.24\)
    2. \(P(\text{teal})=\frac{66}{382}=0.17\)
    3. \(P(\text{house and black})=\frac{40}{382}=0.1\)
    4. \(P(\text{quilt or black})=\frac{141+122-39}{382}=0.59\)
    5. \(P(\text{white given house})=\frac{49}{149}=0.33\)
    6. \(P(\text{quilt given black})=\frac{39}{122}=0.32\)
    7. \(P(\text{teal given house}) = 0.12\) and \(P(\text{teal given rug}) = 0.11\), so a house is more likely to be teal than a rug is.

    • P(WL or LW) = 1-0.4661-0.0861 = 0.4478

  61. Question

    Bob has a 0.25 chance of winning a game. If Bob wins, he has a 0.44 chance of being happy after the game. If Bob loses, he has a 0.25 chance of being happy after the game.

    After the game, you notice Bob is happy. What is the chance that Bob won his game?


    Solution

    (ANS=0.3697479)

    video

    Use the definition of conditional probability. \[P(\text{win given happy}) = \frac{P(\text{win and happy})}{P(\text{happy})}\] We can first determine all the joint probabilities. \[P(A\text{ and }B) = P(A)\cdot P(B\text{ given } A) \] \[\begin{aligned} P(\text{win and happy}) &= 0.25\times0.44 = 0.11\\ P(\text{win and sad}) &= 0.25\times(1-0.44) = 0.14\\ P(\text{lose and happy}) &= (1-0.25)\times0.25 = 0.1875\\ P(\text{lose and sad}) &= (1-0.25)\times(1-0.25) = 0.5625\\ \end{aligned}\]

    Notice there are two mutually exclusive ways Bob could be happy. \[\begin{aligned} P(\text{happy}) &= P\left(\text{[win and happy] OR [lose and happy]}\right) \\ &= P(\text{win and happy}) + P(\text{lose and happy}) \\ &= 0.11+0.1875 \\ &= 0.2975 \end{aligned}\] So, back to the conditional probability. \[P(\text{win given happy}) = \frac{0.11}{0.2975} = 0.37\]

    Bob has a 0.38 chance of winning a game. If Bob wins, he has a 0.85 chance of being happy after the game. If Bob loses, he has a 0.39 chance of being happy after the game.

    After the game, you notice Bob is happy. What is the chance that Bob won his game?


    Solution

    (ANS=0.5718839)

    video

    Use the definition of conditional probability. \[P(\text{win given happy}) = \frac{P(\text{win and happy})}{P(\text{happy})}\] We can first determine all the joint probabilities. \[P(A\text{ and }B) = P(A)\cdot P(B\text{ given } A) \] \[\begin{aligned} P(\text{win and happy}) &= 0.38\times0.85 = 0.323\\ P(\text{win and sad}) &= 0.38\times(1-0.85) = 0.057\\ P(\text{lose and happy}) &= (1-0.38)\times0.39 = 0.2418\\ P(\text{lose and sad}) &= (1-0.38)\times(1-0.39) = 0.3782\\ \end{aligned}\]

    Notice there are two mutually exclusive ways Bob could be happy. \[\begin{aligned} P(\text{happy}) &= P\left(\text{[win and happy] OR [lose and happy]}\right) \\ &= P(\text{win and happy}) + P(\text{lose and happy}) \\ &= 0.323+0.2418 \\ &= 0.5648 \end{aligned}\] So, back to the conditional probability. \[P(\text{win given happy}) = \frac{0.323}{0.5648} = 0.572\]

  71. Question

    A scratch-off lottery ticket has the following payout probabilities:

    payout ($) probability
    0 0.52
    1 0.30
    61 0.09
    79 0.09

    What is the value, in dollars, of the unscratched ticket (to a risk-neutral individual)?


    Solution

    The expected value is the weighted average of the payouts weighted by their probabilities. The expected value is the sum of the products of each payout times its probability.

    \[\mu ~=~ \sum x\cdot P(x)\]

    \[\mu ~=~ (0\cdot0.52)+(1\cdot0.3)+(61\cdot0.09)+(79\cdot0.09)\]

    \[\mu ~=~ 0+0.3+5.49+7.11\]

    \[\mu ~=~ 12.9\]

    A risk-neutral person would value an unscratched ticket at $12.90.

  81. Question

    A ski slope is set up with many interweaving, branching paths in a mesh-like array. A skier starts at the top with two choices: left or right. At the next fork, they can again choose left or right. If the first two decisions are LR (left then right) or RL (right then left), the skier ends up in the same place. That pattern continues down the mountain.


    To get to the lodge, a skier passes 9 forks. They need to make 3 left turns and 6 right turns. To choose a path, the skier just has to choose which 3 of the 9 forks they will turn left. How many possible paths are there to the lodge?


    Solution

    Pascal’s Triangle!


    You can calculate this using a variety of tools.

    • On Desmos you can use nCr(9,3).
    • On a spreadsheet you can use =COMBIN(9,3)

    Using factorial notation we can express the calculation.

    \[\frac{9!}{3! \cdot 6!} ~=~ \frac{9\cdot8\cdot7\cdot6\cdot5\cdot4\cdot3\cdot2\cdot1}{(3\cdot2\cdot1)\cdot(6\cdot5\cdot4\cdot3\cdot2\cdot1)} ~=~ 84\]

    You can also express the calculation using \(\Pi\) product notation.

    \[\frac{~~~\prod\limits_{i=7}^9 i~~~}{\prod\limits_{i=1}^3 i} ~=~ \frac{7\cdot8\cdot9}{1\cdot2\cdot3} ~=~ 84\]
